article.headline: Pippen sits out win
article.linkText: Bulls beat Raptors, nix six-game streak
article.story:
CHICAGO (AP) -- The hugs and handshakes came following the game, after the Chicago Bulls played tough and rough while showing former teammate Jalen Rose they can win without him. Jamal Crawford scored 27 points and the Bulls beat Rose and the Toronto Raptors 96-89 Sunday in the teams' first meeting since a major Dec. 1 trade. "You don't want to lose to your friends and stuff like that," said Chicago's Antonio Davis, a major figure in the six-player deal that sent Rose to the Raptors. "It always presents a little something extra, but I thought we handled it very well." Rose, hounded by Crawford, finished with 22 points for the Raptors but shot just 5-for-12 from the field in his return to Chicago. "It felt a weird at first. He is a guy I looked up to as a youngster. Once the game started, I didn't think about it," said Crawford, who embraced Rose after the game. Toronto has lost five straight and Rose was unhappy on several fronts afterward. "It's a game we wanted to win because we had a big trade against this team and it's a game we're disappointed we didn't get," Rose said. "It's one that's going to stick with us for a minute." Before the game, a greaseboard in the Bulls' locker room contained this quote attributed to Rose: "The Chicago Bulls are the worst team in the league!" Lower down was this: Translation: With the worst players! What Rose really said to Toronto writers was this: "They're the worst team in the league, currently. ... It's a lot better than being on the bottom and looking up and that's where I was in Chicago, for sure." Rose denied the quote the way it was presented on the board. "That's just typical media play, that's typical something that when your team is struggling, you want to do something to get them fired up," Rose said. "Hopefully it takes more than the Raptors to come to town to get those guys fired up than a quote from Jalen Rose that he didn't say." Vince Carter, in his second game back since missing three with a quadriceps injury, shot just 6-of-23 while scoring 14 points. Chris Bosh led the Raptors with 23 points and had 10 rebounds. Carter, guarded by developmental league signee Ronald Dupree, said the losing streak is getting to everyone. "We can play with anybody in the league. We know that and we've shown that. But right now ... It's not fun," Carter said. Toronto is now 12-14 since the trade that sent Rose, Donyell Marshall and Lonny Baxter from Chicago to Toronto for Davis, Jerome Williams and Chris Jefferies. The Raptors are 20-22 overall. The Bulls are 9-19 since the deal and 13-31 for the season. "I think we got the best of the trade because we got a better record," Rose said before the game. "In the NBA you're judged by the standings and right now we're ahead in the standings." Davis was a major factor against his old team Sunday, scoring 14 points, hitting a late jumper, and grabbing 14 rebounds in the rough and physical matchup that had players falling all over the floor. Rose drew some boos during pregame introductions and then went out and missed his first four shots, including a layup. Crawford hit a 3-pointer to put the Bulls up 79-71 with 6:38 to go. Kirk Hinrich's two free throws then pushed the lead to 10 and the Bulls hung on before a sellout crowd to end a six-game losing streak.

Game notes
Marshall had 13 points for the Raptors while Williams went scoreless with six rebounds for the Bulls. ... Scottie Pippen missed the game with a sore knee. ... The Raptors shot just 35 percent for the game to 52 percent for the Bulls.
